The paper deals with the construction of Euclidean spanners, which are a fundamental topic in computational geometry and graph theory. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of the running time and weight of the spanners, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). The paper mentions doubling metrics, which are a type of metric space, indicating that it could also be classified under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper presents a transformation that decreases the lightness of spanners in general metrics, which could place it under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
